<HEADLINE>
<P>
INTO THE NIGHT / BILL HIGGINS: HOFFMAN COULD BE BIG AFTER THIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL HIGGINS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Scene: Wednesday's screening on its 25th anniversary of United Artists' 
"Midnight Cowboy" by the American Film Institute's Third Decade Council. A 
discussion with the filmmakers and a reception followed the screening of the 
only X-rated film ever to win a Best Picture Oscar. "It's a touching, rather 
sweet film," said David Hockney. "It tells you something about censors that 
they would give this an X." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Who Was There: The film's stars, Jon Voight and Dustin Hoffman; co-star Brenda 
Vaccaro; director John Schlesinger; producer Jerome Hellman; plus 500 guests 
including Jodie Foster, AFI's Jean Firstenberg, Ellen Barkin, Barry Levinson, 
Joanna Pakula, Sally Kellerman and studio execs Frank Mancuso, James Middleton 
and John Calley. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Quoted: Hoffman on why the movie probably wouldn't be made today -- "The 
studios want high concept films, which means you have to be able to say in a 
sentence: 'Arnold Schwarzenegger is pregnant in "Twins 2." ' I don't know how 
you explain 'Midnight Cowboy' in one sentence. Jon Voight comes to town to bed 
all the ladies and become rich, but winds up having sex with gay people in the 
street. You'd see the studio execs thinking 'How's that going to open in 2,000 
theaters the first weekend?' Right then you got a problem." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Audience Review: Much praise for the way the film held up. A typical comment 
was "a classic, a masterpiece that will play in the year 3000." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Trend Watch: Maybe the '60s really are coming back. First a 1969 movie is a 
major hit with an audience, then someone smokes pot in the men's room. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Best Anecdote: Schlesinger said an astute mind at the studio wrote a memo 
before the film was made that said, "If we could clean this up and add a few 
songs, it could be a great vehicle for Elvis Presley." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Overheard: When the screening ended, Martin Landau went up to Hoffman and 
said: "When this picture comes out, you're going to be a star." 
</P>
</TEXT>
