<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks and Lily Dizon 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 STILL NOT EASY: Though gay students at Cal State Fullerton and UC Irvine see 
much to be improved, they generally give good marks to their schools . . . this 
according to a new book called "The Gay, Lesbian and Bisexual Students' Guide 
to Colleges, Universities and Graduate Schools," published by New York 
University Press. . . . Gay students surveyed for the book at both colleges 
were unanimous that homophobia was a "serious" problem on their campuses. Yet 
the majority would recommend their schools to other gays. 
</P>
<P>
 HOMEWORK: The gay students surveyed have problems that go beyond campus: A 
majority at Cal State Fullerton -- and a high number at UC Irvine -- say they 
are openly gay on campus, but are not "out" to their parents. And most said 
that "coming out" was the most serious issue among gays on the campus. . . . At 
UC Irvine, 50% said they have been victims of hate mail, vandalism or verbal 
abuse. Another major problem for them: a lack of role models on their campuses. 
</P>
<P>
 RIGHT PITCH: A star softball player at Trabuco Hills High, Linda Lunceford is 
now in her fourth year playing for Cal State Long Beach. But she's got a 
different ball diamond in her future. . . . She'll soon marry Scott Sanders, a 
starting pitcher for the San Diego Padres this year. She hopes to start a 
family and "be supportive" to Sanders' career. "I've known disappointment on 
the ball field," she says with a laugh. "So if that happens, we can share it." 
They plan an October wedding -- after the baseball season ends. 
</P>
<P>
 WAVES OF SHOPPERS? Some cities spend big bucks to put in auto malls to attract 
out-of-town business. In Newport Beach, with its picturesque waterways, 
officials are kicking around something similar, except with boats. . . . 
Assistant City Manager Ken Delino says Newport Beach needs to push itself as a 
nautical center. "What we have is boats," says Delino, "so we're exploring the 
idea of a showcase for boats." As a base, the city has more than 100 boat 
dealers. 
</P>
