<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; MARINE ENVIRONMENT STUDY GETS GO-AHEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The California Coastal Commission approved a three-year study Thursday that 
will examine the state of the marine environment off the coast of Ventura and 
Los Angeles counties and in the Channel Islands National Marine Sanctuary, 
commission spokesman Jack Liebster said. 
</P>
<P>
 The $600,000 study will be funded by Chevron Corp. and its Point Arguello 
corporate partners in compliance with a condition of a 1993 permit to ship oil 
by tanker to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 The study will begin next month and run through February, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
 The commission also approved Chevron's request to annually discharge about 
49,000 barrels of drilling muds and about 29,000 barrels of drill cuttings off 
Platform Gail, situated about 11 miles off the coast of Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 The purpose of the coastal study is to record conditions at shoreline sites to 
be used in the event of an oil spill. The inventory will include wetlands, 
estuaries and other coastal habitats, and will be conducted by scientists at 
UCLA and UC Santa Barbara. 
</P>
<P>
 UCLA Associate Prof. Richard Ambrose said the study will allow scientists and 
others to know which coastal habitats are vulnerable in the event of an oil 
spill. 
</P>
<P>
 In a separate proposal, commission staff members recommended approval of the 
discharge from Platform Gail, saying the discharge produced a smaller threat to 
the environment than shipping the wastes off the platform. 
</P>
<P>
 The oil platform, built in 1987, produces about 4,500 barrels of oil and 
20,000 cubic feet of natural gas a day. Chevron's discharge plan has been 
approved by the federal Environmental Protection Agency. TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</TEXT>
