<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: BASEBALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE, From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Angel starter Joe Magrane, who underwent arthroscopic elbow surgery last week, 
began working out Thursday and could start throwing lightly within two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
 Magrane, whose surgery prompted the Angels to sign Frank Tanana to a triple-A 
contract Tuesday, said the inflammation in his elbow is completely gone.He is 
optimistic that he'll be able to rejoin the Angel rotation by the end of April. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've heard good things," Angel General Manager Bill Bavasi said, "and we're 
very, very encouraged." 
</P>
<P>
 Although the Angels protected themselves by signing Tanana, the risk is 
minimal. Tanana will earn a base salary of $300,000, and will be paid $38,000 
for every game he starts beginning with his seventh. Magrane does not expect to 
miss more than four starts. BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</TEXT>
